  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: The Self-Cleaning White Coat (Mostly)" imageAlt="Japanese Spitz puppy being brushed through its white double coat" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Here's the breed's best-kept secret: that pure-white coat is far easier than it looks. The texture resists dirt the way a good raincoat resists water; mud dries, falls out, and the dog walks back in white. Baths stay occasional, every 4 to 6 weeks or so, because over-washing strips the coat's own protection.</p>
      <p>The honest work is volume, not stains: brush 2 to 3 times a week down to the skin, daily during seasonal coat blows, and make peace with white hair on dark clothing. As with all double-coated breeds, never shave it; the coat insulates against our heat as well as cold, and shaving damages how it grows back. A tidy trim is fine; the clippers are not.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Japanese Spitz Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Japanese Spitz puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Japanese Spitz goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. Health-wise this breed is one of the best stories we get to tell: it is famously robust, with few inherited problems. The points worth knowing are patellar luxation, the kneecap issue shared across small breeds, and runny eyes in some individuals, where daily wipes keep tear staining off the white face; the wipes are in your starter kit.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the puppy health checks explained guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Japanese Spitz's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Japanese Spitz puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Japanese Spitz explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about how our free home delivery and setup works.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and predictable. A fixed feeding routine, the toilet pads where we placed them, and short, gentle play. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and the grin becomes permanent. Book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer this week; early work on the spitz voice pays off for a decade. See what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers. For anything in between, you WhatsApp us.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

